NOTES ON THE GDOS

The following is a list of additions that need to go into the release notes
for GEMDOS ver 1.0.

   1: BDOS function 57: Get/Set Date & Time Stamp specification in 
      the GEM DOS Programmers Guide page 4-49 is incorrectly specified.  
      It should be:

         VOID f_datime (buf, h, set)

   2: BDOS function 43: Get/Set File Attributes specification in the GEM DOS
      Programmers Guide page 4-37 is incorrectly specified.  It should be:

         LONG f_attrib (p, wrt, mod)
            BYTE *p, mod;
            WORD wrt;
         {
         }

                  Parameter Block
            +--------------------------------+ Low Memory (Parameter
            |    Function Code 43H           |             block addr)
            +--------------------------------+
            |    Pointer to string           |
            +                                + Long
            |   containing pathname          |
            +--------------------------------+
            | GET-SET File Attributes        | Word
            +--------------------------------+
            |       ptr to byte buffer       |
            +                                +
            |    containing attributes       |
            +--------------------------------+ High memory

   3: There have been a number of bug fixes to the cli, COMMAND.PRG, as well
      as a number of enhancements in version 0.42.  
      The bug fixes are as follows:

         1: The cli now correctly handles the following command
            copy \foo \foo1 where foo and foo1 are both directories.

         2: The cli (and the system) no longer goes away when a batch file has
            been invoked with output redirected and a program within the batch
            file returns an error condition.  The cli now returns to the {A} 
            prompt.

      The enhancements to the cli are as follows:
         1: The COMMAND.PRG can be invoked with parameters.  These parameters 
            are processed as they would be if they had been typed in at the 
            {A} prompt. The major difference being that when the command has 
            been executed an exit command is executed returning the system to 
            the state it was before COMMAND.PRG was invoked.  This allows .BAT 
            files to be executed from the desktop by assigning a document type 
            of BAT to COMMAND.PRG with INSTALL APPLICATION.

         2: DIR now has a -w option that allows a horizontal terse directory 
            display.

         3: REN and ERA will warn you if you are about to do a wild carded 
            operation showing you exactly what it thinks you meant by the 
            command you typed in.

         4: REN now tells you that it failed if you try to rename a file to an
            exsisting file name.


